            <h2 id="what-is-ocr">What Is OCR and How Does It Work?</h2>
            <p>Optical Character Recognition (OCR) is technology that analyzes an image containing text and identifies what each character is, reconstructing machine-readable text from a visual representation.</p>
            <p>Modern OCR works in several stages:</p>

            <div class="article-steps">
                <div class="article-step">
                    <div class="article-step-badge">Stage 1</div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>Pre-processing</strong>
                        <p>The image is analyzed and corrected — straightening skewed scans, increasing contrast, removing noise and speckles, and converting to optimal grayscale for character detection.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="article-step">
                    <div class="article-step-badge">Stage 2</div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>Layout analysis</strong>
                        <p>The engine identifies regions of text vs images, detects columns and reading order, and segments individual lines and words.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="article-step">
                    <div class="article-step-badge">Stage 3</div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>Character recognition</strong>
                        <p>Each character is analyzed using pattern matching and machine learning models trained on millions of document samples. Modern AI-powered OCR achieves 99%+ accuracy on clear scans.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="article-step">
                    <div class="article-step-badge">Stage 4</div>
                    <div>
                        <strong>Post-processing</strong>
                        <p>The recognized text is spell-checked against language dictionaries, and context-aware corrections are applied. "0" vs "O" and "l" vs "1" ambiguities are resolved using surrounding words.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <p>The result is a "searchable PDF" — the original image is preserved visually, but an invisible layer of machine-readable text is added behind it. You can now search, select, copy, and use the text for conversion.</p>

            <h2 id="when-do-you-need-ocr">When Do You Need OCR?</h2>

            <div class="article-callout article-callout--blue">
                <strong>Quick test:</strong> Open your PDF and try to click and drag to select text. If you can highlight individual words and copy them — your PDF already has readable text and doesn't need OCR. If nothing is selectable, it's an image-based scan that needs OCR.
            </div>

            <p>Common situations where OCR is needed:</p>

            <div class="article-grid-2">
                <div class="article-card">
                    <div class="article-card-icon">📠</div>
                    <strong>Faxed or scanned documents</strong>
                    <p>Any document that was physically scanned or received as a fax is an image — not real text. OCR is required to work with the content.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="article-card">
                    <div class="article-card-icon">📸</div>
                    <strong>Phone photos of documents</strong>
                    <p>Documents photographed with a smartphone are images. OCR converts them to editable, searchable text.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="article-card">
                    <div class="article-card-icon">🗄️</div>
                    <strong>Archived paper records</strong>
                    <p>Historical documents, old contracts, and paper archives scanned for digital storage need OCR to become searchable.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="article-card">
                    <div class="article-card-icon">🔍</div>
                    <strong>Searchable document archives</strong>
                    <p>Building a searchable document library from physical records requires OCR to make each document's content findable.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="article-card">
                    <div class="article-card-icon">✏️</div>
                    <strong>Editing scanned content</strong>
                    <p>If you need to extract data from scanned invoices, contracts, or reports into spreadsheets or databases, OCR is the first step.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="article-card">
                    <div class="article-card-icon">♿</div>
                    <strong>Accessibility compliance</strong>
                    <p>Scanned PDFs are not accessible to screen readers. OCR creates readable text layers that assistive technology can process.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h2 id="factors-affecting-accuracy">Factors That Affect OCR Accuracy</h2>
            <p>OCR accuracy varies enormously depending on the quality of the input document. Understanding what affects accuracy helps you set realistic expectations and prepare documents for better results.</p>

            <div class="article-table-wrap">
                <table class="article-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Factor</th>
                            <th>Impact on Accuracy</th>
                            <th>What to Do</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Scan resolution (DPI)</td>
                            <td>🔴 Very High</td>
                            <td>Scan at 300 DPI minimum; 600 DPI for small text</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Document skew/rotation</td>
                            <td>🔴 Very High</td>
                            <td>Use auto-deskew or rescan straight</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Font clarity &amp; size</td>
                            <td>🟡 High</td>
                            <td>Minimum 10pt font; avoid decorative/handwritten fonts</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Background noise/marks</td>
                            <td>🟡 High</td>
                            <td>Clean scanner bed; use noise removal preprocessing</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Contrast (light vs dark)</td>
                            <td>🟡 High</td>
                            <td>Adjust scanner contrast; avoid faded documents</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Language selection</td>
                            <td>🟠 Medium</td>
                            <td>Select the correct language(s) in OCR settings</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Document age/deterioration</td>
                            <td>🟠 Medium</td>
                            <td>Clean physical document before scanning</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Handwriting</td>
                            <td>🔴 Very High</td>
                            <td>Machine-printed text converts well; handwriting is challenging</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>

            <h2 id="how-to-improve">How to Improve OCR Results</h2>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">1</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Scan at 300 DPI or higher</strong>
                    <p>DPI (dots per inch) is the single biggest factor in OCR accuracy. At 150 DPI, characters are too blurry for reliable recognition. At 300 DPI, modern OCR achieves 97%+ accuracy on clear text. For documents with small fonts, use 600 DPI.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">2</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Ensure the document is straight</strong>
                    <p>Even 2–3 degrees of rotation significantly reduces OCR accuracy. Most scanners have an auto-deskew feature — enable it. If scanning with a phone, make sure the document is flat and the camera is directly overhead, not at an angle.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">3</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Use black and white scanning for text documents</strong>
                    <p>For documents that are primarily text, scanning in black and white (or grayscale) rather than color produces smaller files and often better OCR accuracy. Color scanning makes sense for documents with photos or important color information.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">4</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Select the correct language</strong>
                    <p>OCR engines use language-specific dictionaries and character sets. A document in French will get significantly better results when you specify French rather than defaulting to English. For multilingual documents, select all relevant languages.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">5</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Clean the scanner bed</strong>
                    <p>Dust, smudges, and debris on the scanner glass appear as marks in the scan, which OCR can misinterpret as characters. A clean scanner glass makes a measurable difference in output quality.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h2 id="use-cases">Real-World OCR Use Cases</h2>
            <p>OCR isn't just for making text selectable — here are the high-value workflows where it makes the biggest difference:</p>

            <div class="article-callout article-callout--blue">
                <strong>Invoice data extraction:</strong> OCR a scanned invoice, then use PdfToolStack's <a href="/extract-invoice-data">AI Invoice Extractor</a> to pull out vendor name, invoice number, amounts, and line items into a structured format — eliminating manual data entry.
            </div>

            <div class="article-callout article-callout--orange">
                <strong>Contract review:</strong> OCR a scanned contract to make it searchable and readable, then run it through the <a href="/review-contract">AI Contract Reviewer</a> to identify key clauses, obligations, and risk areas automatically.
            </div>

            <h2 id="after-ocr">What to Do After Running OCR</h2>

            <div class="article-checklist">
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Verify the text is selectable</strong><p>Open the OCR output and try to click and drag to select text. If it works, OCR succeeded.</p></div></div>
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Spot-check accuracy</strong><p>Search for a few specific words you know appear in the document to confirm they were recognized correctly.</p></div></div>
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Check numbers and special characters</strong><p>Digits and symbols are the most common OCR errors. Manually verify any numbers, dates, or currency figures that are important.</p></div></div>
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Convert to Word if you need to edit</strong><p>After OCR, you can use the <a href="/pdf-to-word">PDF to Word converter</a> to get a fully editable document. OCR + conversion is the two-step process for editing any scanned document.</p></div></div>
            </div>

